All rights reserved.\r/n// \r/nusing System;\r/nusing System.IO;\r/nusing System.Text;\r/nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\r/n\r/n\r/n/// <summary>\r/n/// This class uses a symmetric key algorithm (Rijndael/AES) to encrypt and \r/n/// decrypt data. As long as encryption and decryption routines use the same\r/n/// parameters to generate the keys, the keys are guaranteed to be the same.\r/n/// The class uses static functions with duplicate code to make it easier to\r/n/// demonstrate encryption and decryption logic. In a real-life application, \r/n/// this may not be the most efficient way of handling encryption, so - as\r/n/// soon as you feel comfortable with it - you may want to redesign this class.\r/n/// </summary>\r/npublic class RijndaelSimple\r/n{\r/n /// <summary>\r/n /// Encrypts specified plaintext using Rijndael symmetric key algorithm\r/n /// and returns a base64-encoded result.\r/n /// </summary>\r/n /// <param name=\"plainText\">\r/n /// Plaintext value to be encrypted.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"passPhrase\">\r/n /// Passphrase from which a pseudo-random password will be derived. The\r/n /// derived password will be used to generate the encryption key.\r/n /// Passphrase can be any string. In this example we assume that this\r/n /// passphrase is an ASCII string.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"saltValue\">\r/n /// Salt value used along with passphrase to generate password. Salt can\r/n /// be any string. In this example we assume that salt is an ASCII string.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"hashAlgorithm\">\r/n /// Hash algorithm used to generate password. Allowed values are: \"MD5\" and\r/n /// \"SHA1\". SHA1 hashes are a bit slower, but more secure than MD5 hashes.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"passwordIterations\">\r/n /// Number of iterations used to generate password. One or two iterations\r/n /// should be enough.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"initVector\">\r/n /// Initialization vector (or IV). This value is required to encrypt the\r/n /// first block of plaintext data. For RijndaelManaged class IV must be \r/n /// exactly 16 ASCII characters long.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <param name=\"keySize\">\r/n /// Size of encryption key in bits. Allowed values are: 128, 192, and 256. \r/n /// Longer keys are more secure than shorter keys.\r/n /// </param>\r/n /// <returns>\r/n /// Encrypted value formatted as a base64-encoded string.\r/n /// </returns>\r/n public static string Encrypt\r/n (\r/n string plainText,\r/n string passPhrase,\r/n string saltValue,\r/n string hashAlgorithm,\r/n int passwordIterations,\r/n string initVector,\r/n int keySize\r/n )\r/n {\r/n // Convert strings into byte arrays.\r/n // Let us assume that strings only contain ASCII codes.\r/n // If strings include Unicode characters, use Unicode, UTF7, or UTF8 \r/n // encoding.\r/n byte[] initVectorBytes = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes(initVector);\r/n byte[] saltValueBytes = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes(saltValue);\r/n\r/n\r/n // Convert our plaintext into a byte array.\r/n // Let us assume that plaintext contains UTF8-encoded characters.\r/n byte[] plainTextBytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(plainText);\r/n\r/n\r/n // First, we must create a password, from which the key will be derived.\r/n // This password will be generated from the specified passphrase and \r/n // salt value. The password will be created using the specified hash \r/n // algorithm. Password creation can be done in several iterations.\r/n PasswordDeriveBytes password = new PasswordDeriveBytes\r/n (\r/n passPhrase,\r/n saltValueBytes,\r/n hashAlgorithm,\r/n passwordIterations\r/n );\r/n\r/n\r/n // Use the password to generate pseudo-random bytes for the encryption\r/n // key. Specify the size of the key in bytes (instead of bits).\r/n //byte[] keyBytes = password.GetBytes(keySize / 8);\r/n byte[] keyBytes = Encoding.ASCII.GetBytes(\"1234567812345678\");\r/n Console.WriteLine(Encoding.UTF8.GetString(keyBytes));\r/n // Create uninitialized Rijndael encryption object.\r/n RijndaelManaged symmetricKey = new RijndaelManaged();\r/n\r/n\r/n // It is reasonable to set encryption mode to Cipher Block Chaining\r/n // (CBC). Use default options for other symmetric key parameters.\r/n symmetricKey.Mode = CipherMode.ECB;\r/n\r/n\r/n // Generate encryptor from the existing key bytes and initialization \r/n // vector. Key size will be defined based on the number of the key \r/n // bytes.\r/n ICryptoTransform encryptor = symmetricKey.CreateEncryptor\r/n (\r/n keyBytes,\r/n initVectorBytes\r/n );\r/n\r/n\r/n // Define memory stream which will be used to hold encrypted data.\r/n MemoryStream memoryStream = new MemoryStream();\r/n\r/n\r/n // Define cryptographic stream (always use Write mode for encryption).\r/n CryptoStream cryptoStream = new CryptoStream\r/n (\r/n memoryStream,\r/n encryptor,\r/n CryptoStreamMode.Write\r/n );\r/n\r/n\r/n // Start encrypting.\r/n Console.WriteLine(plainTextBytes.Length);\r/n cryptoStream.Write(plainTextBytes, 0, plainTextBytes.Length);\r/n\r/n\r/n // Finish encrypting.\r/n cryptoStream.FlushFinalBlock();\r/n\r/n\r/n // Convert our encrypted data from a memory stream into a byte array.\r/n byte[] cipherTextBytes = memoryStream.ToArray();\r/n\r/n\r/n // Close both streams.\r/n memoryStream.Close();\r/n cryptoStream.Close();\r/n\r/n\r/n // Convert encrypted data into a base64-encoded string.\r/n string cipherText = Convert.ToBase64String(cipherTextBytes);\r/n\r/n\r/n // Return encrypted string.\r/n return cipherText;\r/n }
